Fit a time series model and ran standard prediction for each end point
decline in vax rate slower than I thought a week or two ago, still on track pretty handily

Earlier, I estimated we'd see 11.82B doses given by May 31, and we're at 11.84B. 160.3M to go to reach 12B. 61 days until July 31. An average of at least 160.3M / 61 days = 2.63M/day must be given over June and July for 12B to be reached by July 31. An average of just under 5.0M/day is being given now, so I think this is likely. But I'm feeling less certain about it.
The average over the remaining days through July 31 would need to stay above ~2.86M/day to reach 12B by July 31, and that looks extremely likely to me. ~5.5M/day added in the past week.
Realizing FT may not have final numbers for its most recent days as they seem to have been updated. Still, the downward trend does not seem to be slowing much.
Vax/day rates are dropping precipitously still. OWID went from 10.8 million/day to 6.0 million/day in about 15 days from May 1 to 15. Judging by the FT chart we're now under 4 million/day.
I hate to say it, but it’s starting to look possible that we might need to consider yet another bin later….

The May 13 total at ft.com for data through May 12 is 11.7055B. 294.5M to go to reach 12B. 80 more days of data to July 31. At least 294.5M/80 days = 3.68M/day needed to reach 12B by July 31. The current 7-day average is about twice that. The trend in the 7-day average has slowed about 1.5M/week YTD, but at some point, that will slow. Lately, it looks like decline in the trend has slowed to ~0.9M/week.

I suppose I should add a slight chance that the forecast could tip into bin 4, but I don't think it's likely. The total on the ft.com website today with the 5/12 update is 11.6997B. 300.3M to go to reach 12B. The total on the ft.com website with the 5/5 update was 11.6461B. 53.6M added in the past week, or 7.66M/day. 10.1M/day was added in the week before that (4/28-5/5). An average of 15.8M/day would need to be added to reach 12B by May 31, more than double last week's rate, so I see no chance of bin 2 happening. An average of 3.75M/day will need to be added to reach 12B by July 31. If we get to May 31 with ~186M to go to reach 12B, then 3.05M/day would be needed to reach 12B by July 31, which I think is likely. The decline will slow down at some point, and I suspect LMICs, in particular, will continue vaccinating at a slow but relatively steady pace.@JonathanMann, @yagudin, bin 4?

11.6816B at the ft.com website as of May 10, for data through May 9. 318.4M to go to reach 12B. 318.4M/22 days = 14.5M/day needed to reach 12B by May 31.11.6303B at the ft.com website as of May 3, for data through May 2. An average of 7.3M/day was added at the ft.com website over the past 7 days. This is below the current 7-day average for May 9 at owid, 8.94M/day.An average of 318.4M/83 days = 3.84M/day needed to reach 12B by July 31; I think that should be achievable as vaccinations continue especially in LMICs, and the decline slows. Suppose an average of 6M/day is added through the end of May; then we'd need to see 186M more to reach 12B. An average of 186M/61 days (from June 1 to July 31) = 3.05M/day would be needed to reach 12B by July 31, which I think is likely.

Total on May 9 for data through May 8 is 11.6756M. 324M to go to reach 12B. 14.7M/day would need to be added to the total on the ft.com graph to reach 12B by May 31, substantially higher than what we have been seeing recently (~7-8M/day). So I'm moving to 100%.
We'd need to see 13.2M/day added to the ft.com website to reach 12B by May 31. That's not likely.

Some interesting things going on, Denmark is ending vaccination entirely next week, CDC is withdrawing J&J's vaccine except for exceptional cases, and a new study came out in Nature linking mRNA vaccination to a 25% increase in cardiac arrests in young people, all this points to vaccination rates continuing to go down

The total today at ft.com is 11.6461B for data through 5/4. The total on 4/28 for data through 4/27 was 11.5751. So 71.0M were added to the plot at ft.com in the past week, or an average of 10.1M/day, well below what is needed to reach 12B by May 31. 353.9M remaining to reach 12B. 353.9M/27 days = 13.1M/day would be needed to reach 12B by May 31.

I had missed it but last week Denmark decided to cease its vaccination program on May 15 since it is no longer necessary, with the option of restarting it in the fall if necessary. This is telling and I think a leading indicator of how we should expect vaccinations to trend in the northern hemisphere@belikewater props on being right again, seems like you're ahead of the curve on most every covid question, sometimes by weeks

Maintaining my forecast. Total on the ft.com website as of the May 3 update is 11.6303B. 370M to go to reach 12B. 29 more days of data by May 31. It would take an average of at least 370M/29 days = 12.8M/day to be added to reach 12B by May 31. The total on the ft.com website 7 days ago, on April 26, was 11.5458B. So 84.5M were added in the past week, or 12.07M/day. The 7-day average at owid today for May 2 is 9.62M/day, which is now substantially below the 7-day average of what was added at ft.com.
Trend has shifted to below 10M/day, which resolves this in June.

Just look at @belikewater 's recent comment [1] which makes a strong case for bin 3. I would go even higher, but a lot can change in a month (although it probably won't) and I try to leave a few percentage points for uncertainty in my forecasts if there are unexplored avenues that could become factors (e.g. will there be a successful campaign to change the rate of dosing or some event that triggers greater urgency in this matter).
Well,

Repeating my forecast. 11,534,367,928 total on the website, as updated on April 25. 465.632M to go. 37 days of data to May 31. An average of at least 465.632M/37 days = 12.58M/day would need to be added to the question resolution website to reach 12B by May 31. The 7-day average on April 24 at owid is 11.27M/day as of today. Adding 5% to this to adjust for backreporting gives 11.83M/day, which is still less than 12.58M/day; this is out of an abundance of caution as a previous calculation found the ft.com 7-day average to be 5% lower than the owid 7-day average. I'll compare tomorrow's (April 26's) total at ft.com with that from 2 weeks ago; the total through April 11 available on the ft.com website on April 12 was 11,398,181,371. I'll compare April 27's total with April 20's total; the total through April 19 available on the ft.com website on April 20 was 11.5013B.
initial forecast - I found @belikewater 's comment [1] very convincing, but I'll need to do a deeper dive before I go much higher on bin 3.

Repeating my forecast. The total available today, April 22, with data through April 21, is 11,508,294,296. 491.7M to go as of April 20 data. 40 days to May 31. 491.7M/40 days = 12.29M/day. The current 7-day average on owid is 10.66M/day, which is less than 12.29M/day, and I think the 7-day average will probably continue to fall.
Gonna be close but I have stuffed this forecast by not updating often enough. I was 80% on before June previously

498.7M to go as of April 20 data. 41 days to May 31. 498.7M/41 days = 12.16M/day. The current 7-day average on owid is 10.66M/day, and I think the 7-day average will probably continue to fall. As an alternate check, the source website at ft.com currently shows the total increasing by 121.987M from April 6 to 20, which is equivalent to ~8.7M/day. Even if another 122M were added every 2 weeks, which is likely an overestimate as the rate at which doses are given will likely continue to fall, only 366M more would be added through May 31. That would leave room for a huge 132M data bomb (of increased doses given and/or reported), which is much larger than likely as well. The forecast will need to be watched closely, but I think 12B will probably not be reached before June 1.

11,490,787,883 total as of April 19. 509,212,117 = ~509.212M to go to 12B. 42 days to May 31. The average must stay >= ~509.212M/42 days = ~12.1M/day to reach 12B by May 31 (again, as always, subject to later adjustments from back reporting). The current 7-day average is 10.76M/day, and the trend will likely continue to fall. At 10.76M/day, we're 1.36M/day short of reaching 12B by May 31; at this rate, we'd be about 57M short of 12B by May 31. As the trend in the 7-day average will likely continue to fall substantially in the forecast period (by something like 0.5M-1M/day each week), and as any "data bump" is likely to add no more than ~4M/day*7 days = ~28M, it is looking increasingly likely to me that the question will resolve in bin 3, even if there is a substantially larger data bump.
See beelikewater!

Increasing my forecast for bin 3 slightly. The total on the source website is 11,428,743,897 as of April 13 (it hasn't been updated with data since then). 48 days from April 13 to May 31. 572.256M to go to reach 12B. An average of at least 572.256M/48 days = 11.901M/day would be needed to reach 12B by May 31. The owid 7-day average of doses given as of April 17 is 11.02M/day. The trend in doses/day has been decreasing since the end of last year. In the past 4 weeks, from March 20 to April 17, the 7-day average of doses/day has fallen by about 4.1M. From April 10 to 17, the 7-day average has fallen by 1.31M. As the 7-day average is already below 11.9M/day amidst a falling trend, it is looking increasingly likely that 12B will be reached after May 31. I see that the crowd's forecast for bin 3 is also moving up, and it looks likely that the consensus will flip to bin 3 over the next week or 2.
I think I was probably wrong to bank on an uptick or sustained vaccination rate, although it's not over yet
google as of today

Again, the question will resolve to the earliest date that first shows a number >=12B on the graph on the source website, not to the earliest date that eventually shows a number >=12B after most or all countries have finished backreporting. If this number is first seen on the website on, say, August 15, then the question will most likely resolve to August 14 or 13, when only partial data are available for those dates, not to an earlier date after all the data are in. (Suppose that on August 15, the source website first shows a number >=12B for August 14. And suppose that 10 days later, on August 25, the updated data now show a number >=12B for July 31. The question is already over, and it has resolved to August 14. It will not resolve to July 31 at that point, or to any earlier date after further updates.)

The clarification issued today shows that the data will be evaluated very slightly differently from how I was thinking. My current understanding is now that when a number >=12B *first* appears on the source website graph, the question will resolve. It will resolve to the earliest date for which a number >=12B appears on the graph - which may or may not be the day before. This means that there will likely not be a large difference between the date on which a number >=12B first appears on the website graph and the date for which the graph shows >=12B was first reached. It could potentially be somewhat large (a few days? a week?) if some country made a gigantic data backreporting drop, but given typical data movements, it is not likely to be more than 1 or 2 days. It appears that data will likely be evaluated for this question before nearly all back reporting has occurred. This is consistent with the fact that no statement was made in the original question saying that data for a given date would be accessed on some specific, later date (e.g., 14 days later, or whatever). I have asked for one more clarification to be sure.

571.256M to go as of April 13 data. 48 days remaining to May 31. An average of at least 571.256M / 48 days = 11.901M / day would need to be maintained to reach 12B by May 31. Current 7-day average is 12.23M/day and slowly falling.

Maintaining my forecast. 576.993M to go to reach 12B as of April 12. 49 days to May 31. So an average of at least 576.993M / 49 days = 11.775M/day must be maintained over the period to May 31 to reach 12B by May 31. The current 7-day average is 12.44M. The trend is solidly downward by roughly 0.75M/week and should be below 11.775M/day within a week, but the numbers could easily bump one or more times again for a while with data from individual countries; the data are very noisy.
Hedging a little bit just to avoid being overconfident
11,398,181,371 as of April 11. 601,818,629 to go. 50 days between April 11 and May 31. 601,818,629/50 days = 12,036,373/day.
54 days from April 7 to May 31, with 625M to go to reach 12B. 625M/54 days = 11.57M/day. If the average is above this, 12B will be reached. On April 7, the 7-day average was 13.32M/day.

I'm expecting rates to decline but not steadily, considering countries like India and China could dramatically change the situation within a few days. Other territories like Europe, South America and Africa are looking more consistent, and supply seems to be relatively reliable as well. I'm still forecasting the last week of May, as I have been for a while, but my best estimate (FWIW) is around 25th May - 2rd June, later than the crowd expects.

Lots of sources from which more vaccinations may come over the next few months. Southern hemisphere will be experiencing its first Omicron winter. India may be authorizing boosters for the first time which would be huge. Unless China pushes a fourth dose, there are fewer possibilities for new vax there than I had originally expected as their booster rate is actually pretty high. In general I don't see vax rate dropping by half from what it is now, and in a fast enough time period to matter, which is roughly what would be required for B2 to fail. But I am bumping up B3 very slightly because China does not seem to be adding more vaccine like I had expected.

Expecting a substantial drop soon. The total could end up very close, but I think bin 3 is more likely. 706.8M to go to reach 12B, as of March 31. 61 days to go to May 31. 706.8M/61 days = 11.6M/day. To reach 12B by May 31, the average over the next 61 days must stay above 11.6M/day. I think it is likely that the average will drop below that in April. The constant upticks are wonderful for people but nerve-wracking for this forecast, because I don't think we'll reach 12B in bin 2. I hope I'm wrong. https://ourworldindata.org/explorers/coronavirus-data-explorer?time=2021-10-15..latest&facet=none&pickerSort=asc&pickerMetric=location&Metric=Vaccine+doses&Interval=7-day+rolling+average&Relative+to+Population=false&Color+by+test+positivity=false&country=Europe~Africa~South+America~North+America~PHL~Asia~OWID_WRL~Lower+middle+income~CHN~IND~IDN~MEX
Adjusting for data correction.
(Duplicated forecasts by mistake.)

11.135B as of March 22. 865M to go to reach 12B. 70 days between March 22 and May 31. The average daily administration must be >= 865M/70 days = 12.36M/day to reach 12B by May 31. This is down 0.31M/day from 12.67M 4 days ago, which is pretty close. The world vaccination rate is generally declining. If it declined linearly, then we'd need to reach ~12.36M/day before ~35 days from now to end up below 12M by May 31. But the world vaccination rate will likely decline a bit more slowly than linearly, so we'd need to reach ~12.36M/day at least a few days before that. On Feb 22, the 7-day average of doses/day was 22.53M; this could be considered above a trend that would have been approx 19M/day then. On March 22, it was 15.74M. If one uses the more conservative drop of 3.25M/day over 4 weeks and project this linearly forward, then in 28 days, we should be at a trend level of ~12.5M doses/day. This forecast may end up close, but I think bin 3 is most likely.

At current uptake rates, it would be another three months to cross 12 billion doses. With the decline in public perception of the virus, there is an increasing chance that this question resolves unsettled.

For anyone wondering how we went back from 11.05B on Mar 18 to 11.02B on Mar 22, the answer is that OWID (upon which FT largely lies) somehow "lost" again the Indonesian data after Dec 31 (they had corrected it after I pinged them https://twitter.com/desertnaut/status/1503549176260571139 , but somehow the omission is back; will ping them again).

It seems like India is considering offering booster doses to all of its adults. If that happens, we could be looking at a big increase in administered vaccine doses soon. https://www.reuters.com/world/india/india-considers-widening-covid-booster-effort-all-adults-sources-say-2022-03-21/
Omicron probably hits the southern hemisphere over winter + big China wave means vax rates will not drop much more

950M left to go to reach 12B. The Philippines recently reported an uptick in vaccinations, but otherwise, the trend is still downwards. China has increased vaccination administration very modestly. 75 days between March 17 and May 31. The average daily administration rate will have to stay above 12.67M/day for the question to resolve in bin 2. The Philippines and China are the largest question marks in my mind, but if their vaccination rates stay relatively flat, then I think bin 3 is likely. (The Philippines has fully vaccinated 64.7M and is targeting 90M "by June"; they will add at most ~51M doses.) 4 weeks ago, on Feb 17, the 7-day average of doses/day was 25.52M; on March 17, it was 17.18M/day, a drop of 8.34M/day. 17.18M/day (now) - 12.67M (average needed to stay in bin 2) = 4.51M/day. We could potentially see below 12.67M/day less than a month from now. https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2022/02/22/2162588/task-force-focus-house-house-mobile-covid-19-vaccination-jab-more-people
The data for Indonesia have now been added to FT (OWID updated them a few hours after I tweeted them, https://twitter.com/desertnaut/status/1503549176260571139 ), for a total of 11.01B as of Mar 14.
well spotted @ctsats
Correcting back towards bin #2—thanks to @ctsats for pointing out the “ticking data bomb in the room”: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1415739
It would seem that we have to do with a data bomb, and a nuclear one indeed...

Repeating my earlier forecast. I have also just submitted a request for clarification to the admins: "Given that the numbers reported in the question resolution data are revised from one day to the next for a given date, when will the question resolution data be looked at to resolve this question? For example, on June 1, the question resolution data could say that on May 31, the total was 11.967B, which would push the question into bin 3. But then on June 3, the question resolution data could be revised to say that on May 31, the total was 12.027B. Or vice versa." I think the real danger is actually probably weeks out, as some countries' reporting is always weeks behind.
Agreeing with arguments and evidence pointed out by @belikewater and @paulm e.g., the post and comments here: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1415262
Question resolution data updated to a total of 10.908B for March 13. This makes bin 3 slightly more likely.

This is getting a little tight. I've been expecting an overall decline since the first forecast, but as per yesterdays comment India has halved their daily rate in the last month, and China has eased as well. While I think China will increase (due to a major outbreak) this helps push the deadline to end of May or into June. I can foresee outcomes where Asia collectively does not maintain an increase long enough to keep us in bin2, so I am hedging towards bin 3. The Philippines show incomplete data but with uptake increasing towards end of Feb - it will be interesting to see if a correction helps boost totals. Thanks for the prompt to re-evaluate @ctsats @belikewater

Updating from my forecast earlier today with the updated source data. 0.096B given in the week ending March 12, and falling. 11 weeks, 3 days to May 31. 10.975B as of March 12. 10.975B + 11.43*0.0975B = 12.089B. This would be over 12B by <1 day of data. However, vaccinations are generally falling worldwide, so bin 3 is looking increasingly likely.
Rough rationale below: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1415012

China is now suffering a big outbreak which could lead to increases in vaccination. I'm surprised the vaccination rate in India has slowed substantially - I had expected a decline but it has halved within a month, which has helped slow the overall rate below 18M/day. I'm still expecting last week of May, but this could easily slip into June if major territories don't maintain a more consistent rate from now on.

0.087B given in the week ending March 10, and falling. 11 weeks, 6 days to June 1. 10.932B as of March 10. 10.932B + 12*0.087B = 11.976B. Bin 3 is looking increasingly likely, as vaccination rates continue to fall. Alternatively, if we look at the data here: https://ourworldindata.org/explorers/coronavirus-data-explorer?time=2021-08-04..latest&facet=none&pickerSort=asc&pickerMetric=location&Metric=Vaccine+doses&Interval=7-day+rolling+average&Relative+to+Population=false&Color+by+test+positivity=false&country=~OWID_WRL we see that ~18M doses/day were recently given, with this number falling off. 12B - 10.932B = 1.068B. 1.068B/12 weeks = 0.089B/week average for 12B to be reached in bin 3. 0.089B/week = 12.7M/day. Recent totals have been driven by Asia, primarily by LMIC countries + China. The data are noisy, but it looks likely to me that the world average #doses/day will fall to ~12.7M/day by around 6 weeks from now and will likely continue to fall overall after that, placing the total in bin 3.
We've dropped way down and I am adjusting way up.

The last week of May now looks most plausible: declining uptake in India, which appears more lead by inclination than availability; a stable uptake in China which I think is unlikely to greatly increase short term. Africa is also back to a steady ~1.8M/day. I think the United States and Europe will continue to slow towards a plateau, helping produce a global decline of approx 75% current levels through April. At today's rate we would reach 12B from 10.88B in ~8 weeks, but with the expected decline I estimate 11-12 weeks, or perhaps just into 1st week June.

With respect to poorer unvaccinated countries, which are the countries that we might expect to account for the growth in the number of vaccine doses administered worldwide now that rich western countries are "done" with covid, the issue also seems to be demand rather than supply (https://www.euractiv.com/section/coronavirus/news/covax-vaccine-supply-outstrips-demand-for-the-first-time/). This suggests that we shouldn't expect supply chains becoming unblocked to translate to a big increase in the daily vaccination rate. As others like @belikewater have remarked, the daily vaccine administration rate has been falling again recently (https://ourworldindata.org/covid-vaccinations#how-many-doses-are-administered-daily), so bin 3 is back into play. This question has involved a few twists and turns after all...
0.093B/week in the past week. 12 weeks 3 days to May 31 => 11.997B. Vaccination rates seem to be falling.
10.8 billion and running at about 25mil per day reasonably steady. So about 50 days needed? Looking unlikely to make it in March unless rate significantly increases.

Bin 2 seems overwhelmingly likely at this point, 3 months for ~1.2B vaccines with (hopefully) rich western countries finally delivering vaccines to countries that have not yet had the chance to acquire vaccines.
Realizing that the FT data are very different from the OWID data.... ugh.
The data are so erratic! I think I will have a terrible score on this forecast in the end.

My favorite data viz source at owid disappeared.

Middle of May still looks likely; China has increased dose rates but this looks unsustainable due to their high vaccination level. Other big territories all look to be creating a net decline after a big increase in Pakistan. My target is approx 10-12 weeks. If the rate slows any more quickly Bin 3 will become more likely.
Diminishing marginal uptake suggests that the forecast date for crossing 12B is now May 11th.
It had looked to me like China was increasing vaccinations, but I just saw another presentation of the data that make it clear that there was a data dump on one day. So, raising bin 3.
Momentum is slowing.
Quite dissapointed in my forecast on this questions for: a; overconfidence b; lack of updating c; narrowing my options early

At the current weekly vaccination rate, we'd see 12.004B on May 31. But of course, vaccination rates aren't static. Vaccination rates continue to decline in N America, S America and Europe. Africa, with a population of just under 70% of those of N America, S America and Europe combined, continues to vaccinate at a low and slightly decreasing rate. India's vaccinations are following a generally declining but very noisy trend. China is currently the driving force, and as I wrote below, they're in some vaccination push. How big of a push that will be remains to be seen.

China seems to be doing a big vaccination push. The net total of everywhere else has been declining to such an extent that bin 3 was looking most likely. But since Feb 6, China seems to have been making a big vaccination push. So, I'll revise up on bin 2 for now.

China has increased vaccination rates significantly in the last few days, and as their population is around 18% of the world's total this increase will affect the outcome. I'd expect the rise to level off, as they are already over 85% fully vaccinated according to ourworldindata.org, but not with a high level of confidence. With other continents still vaccinating at a relatively steady rate I still place the end date very close to the beginning of April,
mid march?

Vaccination rates had been falling, but there has now been an uptick in the vaccination rate in China/Asia. 0.106027B added for the world in the past week. 16 weeks until May 31. Current total = 10.250B. 10.250B + 16 weeks * 0.106027B/week = 11.946B. I'll need to watch to see how this goes over the next few weeks, but if the overall trend continues downward, then it'll be bin 3.

Going to 50/50 on bin2/3. The vaccination rate is falling as highlighted by @belikewater (https://ourworldindata.org/covid-vaccinations#how-many-covid-19-vaccine-doses-are-administered-daily), but supply issues for the poorer countries that have not had the opportunity to vaccinate much of their population may ease in time for bin 2.

The world vaccination rate is falling rapidly. In 2-3 days, the rate will likely fall below the average level needed to stay in bin 2. And I don't see any reason why it will bounce back up much before June.
@belikewater really has a point (again)… https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1392056

As a simplistic guide, India and China both contribute around 18% of global population. China is now highly vaccinated (over 80% supposedly), and the daily rate has slowed markedly in the last few days, while India is only just over 50% fully vaccinated, with the uptake rate holding more steady. I think this generalisation is to be expected, with the rapid tapering more noticeable in highly dosed populations where the Omicron wave is easing. I put 12B reached in around 16 weeks, during last two weeks of May, but this could slip into the beginning of June.

0.26% of the world population was vaccinated on Feb 2, and this figure has been dropping. 57 days until April 1. 7.9B people *.0026/day*57 days + 10.14B = 11.31B < 12B. At today's rate, it will take (12-10.14)/(7.9*0.0026) = 91 days to reach 12M, which is May 5. However, if the current rate continues to drop, we could well end up in bin 3, for which most of us have had a forecast of 0% for a while, lol.

Going up on bin 2. The current issues with producing and supplying vaccines to the unvaccinated world seem to be structural and unlikely to change in the short term covered by bin 1. Today's chartbook is insightful https://adamtooze.substack.com/p/chartbook-77-more-than-7000-deaths .

Currently at 10.08 billion. That means to hit 12 million we need to reliably exceed about 32 million / day. I'm updating down again here. Unless we start hitting that number soon, it starts to look at lot less likely.
The Covid virus is incredibly smart and will continue to alter it’s formation, therefore developing differ variants for a very long time.

Going down a bit following @paulm, but I don't think bin 1 is too unlikely yet. Many western countries bought a bunch of vaccines that are now unused as the booster rollout slows down as Omicron becomes less threatening. These vaccines may provide a boost to worldwide vaccination numbers if they are donated before their expiry date. On the other hand, countries may be waiting out for the Omicron specific booster that should arrive soon, which may delay any increase in the vaccination rate...
Following the observation/conclusion of @paulm here. Kudos for noticing this slow-down early!
(Mistake.)

0.19467M doses given from Jan 15-21. At this rate, I would expect to see 11.79M doses given by April 1. If Omicron starts spreading widely, as I suspect will be the case, then I suspect many who would have gotten vaccinated may decide not to, while they wait for an Omicron vaccine. While Delta is still spreading, it is good to get vaccinated with the current vaccine, but many who are vaccine hesitant in the first place probably won't. And Omicron vaccines supposedly won't start to be available until mid-March, and probably won't be widely available until somewhere around June. I'm not sure what the net here is, but I suspect that if Omicron replaces Delta, there will be a surge in Omicron vaccine uptake as it becomes available. So, if Omicron spreads, then perhaps we'll see a slight slowing in the rate of vaccine uptake through March, followed by an upsurge. Production capabilities are increasing, and demand will be high.
